The value of \(n\) ranges from 1 to 10. We then need to find the remainder when this count \(K\) is divided by 10. Key steps: 1. **Understanding the sequences**: Each element in the universal set \(\{1, 2, \ldots, 10\}\) can be included at some position \(i\) in the sequence or never be included. Once an element is included at position \(i\), it must be included in all subsequent sets. 2. **Counting the sequences**: For each element, there are 11 choices (positions 1 to 10 or never included). However, the sequence length \(n\) can vary from 1 to 10. The number of sequences of length \(n\) is \((n+1)^{10}\) because each element has \(n+1\) choices (positions 1 to \(n\) or never). 3. **Summing over all possible lengths**: The total number of sequences \(K\) is the sum of \((n+1)^{10}\) for \(n\) from 1 to 10. This sum is \(2^{10} + 3^{10} + \cdots + 11^{10}\). 4. **Calculating modulo 10**: We compute each term modulo 10 and sum the results: - \(2^{10} \equiv 4 \mod 10\) - \(3^{10} \equiv 9 \mod 10\) - \(4^{10} \equiv 6 \mod 10\) - \(5^{10} \equiv 5 \mod 10\) - \(6^{10} \equiv 6 \mod 10\) - \(7^{10} \equiv 9 \mod 10\) - \(8^{10} \equiv 4 \mod 10\) - \(9^{10} \equiv 1 \mod 10\) - \(10^{10} \equiv 0 \mod 10\) - \(11^{10} \equiv 1 \mod 10\) 5. **Summing the results**: Adding these values modulo 10 gives \(4 + 9 + 6 + 5 + 6 + 9 + 4 + 1 + 0 + 1 = 45\). The remainder when 45 is divided by 10 is 5. Thus, the remainder when \(K\) is divided by 10 is \(\boxed{5}\).
